the various positions he took as a champion of the beleaguered Hindu community, an anticaste progressive, an erudite if polemical historian, a pioneering advocate for women’s dignity, and a patriotic poet. This critical examination of Savarkar’s thought shows that Hindutva is as much about the aesthetic experiences that have been attached to the idea of India itself as it is a militant political program that has targeted the Muslim community in pursuit of power in postcolonial India.By bringing to light the many legends surrounding Savarkar, Bakhle shows how this figure from a provincial locality in colonial India rose to world-historical importance. Savarkar and the Making of Hindutva also uncovers the vast hagiographic literature that has kept alive the myth of Savarkar as a uniquely brave, brilliant, and learned revolutionary leader of the Hindu nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAuthors, Marathiy20th centuryvBiography. 0aHindutva. 0aIntellectualszIndiavBiography. 0aNationalistszIndiavBiography. 0aRevolutionarieszIndiavBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Political.2bisacsh  aBrahminism.  aEssentials of Hindutva.  aEthnic nationalism.  aGandhi and Savarkar.  aGandhi.  aHindu community.  aHindu fundamentalism.  aHindu nationalism.  aHindutva.  aMaharashtra and Hindu nationalism.  aMarathi nationalism.  aMuslim community.  aRightwing Hindu nationalism.  aSavarkar and Caste.  aSavarkar and Hindutva.  aSavarkar and Muslims.  aSavarkar and fascism.  aSavarkar biography.  aSavarkar.  aTerritorial fundamentalism.  aTilak and Savarkar.  aTilak.  aZionism and Hindutva.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311074975540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780691251486?locatt=mode:legacy40uhtt